AGENTIC-VT 1.0

[metadata]
title: The First Prompt-Based Audio Plugin That Turns Ideas Into Instruments/FX
channel: @octopusinc_
source: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I1_I1C5pCC4
upload_date: 20260203
transcript_source: captions
route: text

---

[00:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'That wasn\'t three plugins. That was one. And&nbsp; I didn\'t code any of them. Hi, I\'m Leo from&nbsp;&nbsp; Artists in DSP and we just built something that I&nbsp; honestly didn\'t think was possible. It\'s an audio&nbsp;&nbsp; plug-in that can be turned into any audio effect&nbsp; or MIDI instrument you want just by describing&nbsp;&nbsp; it. Here\'s the thing about plugins. They are&nbsp; static. You buy a reverb, you get that reverb.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You want a different algorithm, that\'s another&nbsp; plug-in. If you are a developer, the cycle is&nbsp;&nbsp; brutal. An idea is followed by months of coding.&nbsp; Then there\'s the release and immediately think&nbsp;&nbsp; of 10 better ideas you don\'t have time to build&nbsp; because you\'re already working on the next thing.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'There are basically infinite good DSP ideas out&nbsp; there and it\'s literally impossible to make a&nbsp;&nbsp; dedicated plug-in for all of them. One day we&nbsp; got emailed from a user called 60 Hz. He said,&nbsp;&nbsp; "I have a challenge for you and I\'m sure this&nbsp; will come in the future, but maybe you can be&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the first to accomplish it. Poly and endless have&nbsp; just been released and this is a genius idea,&nbsp;&nbsp; but too bad it is only for hardware right now.&nbsp; So if you can make it work for VST3, I\'m sure it&nbsp;&nbsp; will have a huge joy for you. Poly and Endless is&nbsp; a customizable hardware effect platform. You can&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'create or download huge range of effects and its&nbsp; most interesting feature is the prompt system.&nbsp;&nbsp; An AI playground where you can generate effects&nbsp; by describing them. But there are limits. It\'s&nbsp;&nbsp; hardware. It\'s focused on guitar processing. No&nbsp; MIDI instruments, no deep automation, no session&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'recall, and no complex routing. 60 Hz was right.&nbsp; Doing something like this as a VST could actually&nbsp;&nbsp; change how we build and use plugins. The problem&nbsp; is VSTs are compiled. You can\'t just rewrite the&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'DSP code while the plug-in is running. If you&nbsp; try, you crash the door instantly. And running&nbsp;&nbsp; AI directly inside a plug-in would require&nbsp; server infrastructure and subscription models,&nbsp;&nbsp; something that we really want to avoid. So,&nbsp; for a while, I honestly thought this was a hard&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'limitation of audio software. Great idea, but&nbsp; impossible in practice. Eventually, we started&nbsp;&nbsp; pulling things apart, looking at how real-time&nbsp; audio threads work, how compilers handle DSP, how&nbsp;&nbsp; you could safely swap algorithms without touching&nbsp; the audio thread itself. After lots of trials and&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'errors, we eventually got a first working&nbsp; prototype running. The controlled DSP sandbox&nbsp;&nbsp; that can safely compile and swap algorithms in&nbsp; milliseconds without crushing the host. And once&nbsp;&nbsp; I saw what it could do, I knew I had to show it.&nbsp; This is a morph. It looks like a normal plug-in&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because in this mode it is. But if I click this&nbsp; button, we go into lab mode. This is the workshop,&nbsp;&nbsp; the code editor, and the setup. And here\'s the&nbsp; important part. You don\'t have to code to use&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Amorph. The workflow is simple. Amorph gives&nbsp; you a prompt. You describe what you want to an&nbsp;&nbsp; LLM. Paste the result back here. Hit compile.&nbsp; That\'s it. Now, if you do want to go deeper,&nbsp;&nbsp; the language in this editor is C major, a DSP&nbsp; language made for audio. It\'s built around a&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'straightforward idea. A processor, audio input and&nbsp; output and parameters with all the parameters that&nbsp;&nbsp; you can define with the ranges and names that&nbsp; becomes your real knobs in the user interface.&nbsp;&nbsp; So to create a new instrument inside a morph,&nbsp; first I name it and define the controls I want&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'on the screen. I am going to set the parameters&nbsp; count to zero. So the code will define the knobs&nbsp;&nbsp; using annotations and the AI will generate those&nbsp; annotations for us. I click AI prompt that copies&nbsp;&nbsp; a ready to use prompt with a parameter map and the&nbsp; rules Amorph expects. Now it\'s time to open LLM.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You can use Gemini, Chat GPT, Claude or whatever&nbsp; you want. Just paste the prompt and describe the&nbsp;&nbsp; instrument you want. Let\'s create something quite&nbsp; challenging. A warm arpeggiated poly-synth that&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'locks with the DAW tempo. I prepared already a&nbsp; detailed prompt for the parameters I want to have.&nbsp;&nbsp; I really suggest to be detailed if you want a&nbsp; good sounding result. A quick note, we keep the&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'AI outside of the plug-in right now on purpose so&nbsp; you can use whatever model you like and you stay&nbsp;&nbsp; in control. Once the language model generated the&nbsp; code, you can paste it back into Amorph. Then hit&nbsp;&nbsp; compile. If all went good, you can read in the&nbsp; logger that the compile successfully. If not,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you can just copy the error and give it&nbsp; a second try. In my case, we are done.&nbsp;&nbsp; The algorithm is running and the morph has&nbsp; become that instrument. Now let\'s listen how it Heat.'

[05:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, here\'s a huge part of the workflow, the&nbsp; presets. At the top level, amorph presets are&nbsp;&nbsp; the entire algorithm. So, that\'s the code, the&nbsp; knob names, and the whole device. Think of it&nbsp;&nbsp; like building your own personal rack of synth&nbsp; and effect inside one plug-in. And inside each&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[05:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'algorithm, you can also save parameter snapshots.&nbsp; Those don\'t change the code. They just recall&nbsp;&nbsp; the knob state instantly. Does it work perfectly&nbsp; every time? No. Sometimes the AI can generate code&nbsp;&nbsp; that doesn\'t compile. Maybe a parameter range is&nbsp; wrong. Maybe the math is off. When that happens,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[05:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you see it in the logger. You copy the error&nbsp; or the behaviour. You paste it back into the&nbsp;&nbsp; AI and say fixes. In most cases, one or two&nbsp; iterations and it\'s solid. So, right now,&nbsp;&nbsp; the plug-in supports MIDI input and audio mono&nbsp; and stereo. That means that everything in between&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[05:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'audio effects, MIDI instruments, and weird&nbsp; hybrids can be created. Since building this,&nbsp;&nbsp; I personally have already created around 30&nbsp; different plugins and some are quite simple&nbsp;&nbsp; like basic filters, basic synthetizers and some&nbsp; are very not simple. We even took some ideas&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from the community and tried to regenerate some&nbsp; plugins like Vinyl scratchers, realtime scrubbers,&nbsp;&nbsp; and the interesting part of this, I\'m building&nbsp; plugins I would never have bothered making before&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because when something takes 5 minutes instead&nbsp; of weeks, suddenly lot more ideas become worth&nbsp;&nbsp; trying. But let\'s talk about what this can\'t do&nbsp; because there are some limitations. First of all,&nbsp;&nbsp; the UI is simple. Right now, it\'s knobs&nbsp; and readouts. No fancy graphics or costume&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'visualisers. Sound comes first. That\'s the goal.&nbsp; Visual customization could come later if there\'s&nbsp;&nbsp; demand, but it\'s not the priority. Second, this&nbsp; plug-in isn\'t made for running machine learning&nbsp;&nbsp; models or loading massive sample libraries. It\'s&nbsp; focused on digital signal processing, filters,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'modulations, synthesis, time-based effects, and&nbsp; also MIDI synthetizers. But you really cannot&nbsp;&nbsp; generate sample based processing, at least yet.&nbsp; It\'s it\'s not made for this. If not coding by&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[07:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'yourself and relying only on AIS, you also need to&nbsp; be somehow specific about what you ask for. If you&nbsp;&nbsp; ask the AI for a filter that sounds good, you\'ll&nbsp; probably get something unusable. If you ask for&nbsp;&nbsp; a stable variable filter with 12 dB per octave&nbsp; with resonance, you\'ll get exactly that. And if&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[07:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you\'re new to audio, that\'s fine, too. We already&nbsp; have good presets, and the idea is that presets&nbsp;&nbsp; will be shared by the community. So, even without&nbsp; deep technical knowledge, you\'ll still be able to&nbsp;&nbsp; explore, tweak, and learn from what others build.&nbsp; You\'re probably wondering how much this will cost.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[07:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We talked about it a lot as a team, and we all&nbsp; agreed on one thing. We\'re going to release it for&nbsp;&nbsp; free. We don\'t want to limit creativity. We want&nbsp; everyone to be able to use it, experiment with it,&nbsp;&nbsp; and create amazing and probably weird stuff with&nbsp; it. Right now, we\'re finishing some refinements,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[07:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and after that, we\'ll open it up as an&nbsp; open beta. If you want early access,&nbsp;&nbsp; the link is in the description. So, here\'s&nbsp; what I want to know. What would you build if&nbsp;&nbsp; you could describe it in one sentence and have&nbsp; it running in 2 minutes? I don\'t know if this&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[08:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is the future of plugins, but it\'s definitely a&nbsp; future, and I want to see how far we can push it.'
